# AI Memory System

The AI Memory system is the intelligence backbone of personalization.

It remembers how users learn.

---

# Product Vision

AI Memory must:

- store long-term learning patterns
- improve personalization over time
- track user weaknesses
- adapt AI responses dynamically
- support contextual recall

---

# Memory Types

1. Short-term session memory
2. Long-term learning memory
3. Preference memory
4. Performance memory
5. Concept mastery memory

---

# Architecture

Presentation Layer

↓

MemoryController (Riverpod)

↓

MemoryState

↓

MemoryRepository

↓

Vector Store + Structured DB

---

# State Management

MemoryState includes:

- loading
- syncing
- updated
- error

Core Data:

- userConceptGraph
- weakAreas
- masteredTopics
- preferences
- interactionHistory

---

# Memory Graph

The system builds:

- concept relationships
- performance links
- revision frequency patterns

---

# AI Integration

AI uses memory to:

- personalize explanations
- adjust difficulty
- recommend content
- avoid repeating mastered concepts

---

# Privacy Rules

- user controls memory
- memory can be cleared
- sensitive data is never stored
- full transparency required

---

# Offline Behaviour

- local memory cache
- sync when online
- conflict resolution required

---

# API Contracts

GET /memory

POST /memory/update

DELETE /memory/clear

GET /memory/insights

---

# Analytics Events

memory_updated

memory_cleared

memory_used_in_response

memory_insight_generated

---

# UX Rules

- memory must be invisible but impactful
- users should not feel system complexity
- provide optional memory summary view

---

# Performance

- memory retrieval <100ms target
- updates must be async

---

# Accessibility

Must support:

- readable memory summaries
- accessible insight panels

---

# Testing Requirements

Unit Tests:

Memory graph logic

Preference storage

Concept linking

Widget Tests:

Memory insights UI

Preference views

Integration Tests:

AI personalization flow

Memory-driven recommendation flow

---

# Cursor Instructions

When generating AI memory features:

- always treat memory as adaptive system
- always respect privacy controls
- always use memory to improve AI outputs
- never expose raw memory graph directly to UI